Project Title: Project Management Fighting Game Tournament Project
Date: January 25
Prepared by: Team Holy Moly - Raul Plascencia, Kristen Wakamoto, Daniel Lobato, Jeremy Anoc
Project Summary and Justification: The team members conceived this project to assist Team Holy Moly in meeting its strategic goals. Promoting and conducting a fighting game tournament at UCI’s ZotZone will allow Team Holy Moly to gain experience and apply lessons learned from Project Management to a real-world situation. This project is within Team Holy Moly’s capability. We already have a venue for holding the tournament, and the cost for reserving this venue will easily be met. The budget for the project is $41, and no additional expenses will be necessary after the project’s completion. It is important for the project to cover, at minimum, the $41 of expenses.
Product Characteristics and Requirements: 
Venue: The venue chosen for this project event is ZotZone. ZotZone is located in the student center on the second floor, which serves as the main floor and is accessed through ring road. This venue was chosen due to its main purpose of hosting gaming tournaments previously and having the resources to make this project event possible at an affordable price point.
Xbox rentals: The tournament requires the use of multiple Xboxes, since that is the platform that the games must run on. There will be at least 3 Xbox consoles hosting matches simultaneously to ensure that the tournament is progressing as best possible. The Xbox rentals are priced at $1 per hour, as well as a $1 non refundable deposit for each. They will be rented for the entire duration of the event.
Promotional supplies: To promote this event the use of flyers, a Facebook event page, and perhaps a poster must be utilizes to bring attention and attract potential players. 
Prizes: Prizes will be offered in order to provide some incentive to gamers who are participating in this event. The prizes are in the form of monetary rewards for placing first, second and third. In the event that not many players join the tournament, the prize will only go to the first place winner. The cash for the monetary reward will be provided through the entrance fees of all contestants.
Communication with competitors: In the case of having to make announcements about the tournament project to participants we will be asking for emails addresses from everyone. Furthermore, the Facebook event page will also be utilized for this same purpose being perhaps the easiest method of communicating with others in a manner which most will see fairly quickly.
Summary of Project Deliverables:
Project management-related deliverables: Communication covenant/team contract, business case, scope statement, WBS, lessons learned, final project presentation
Product-related deliverables:
Flyers: Paper flyers will be created  in order to bring attention to the event and hopefully draw in contestants.
Promotion: We are going to use social media and word of mouth to make sure the information about the tournament reaches every single potential player.
Prize money: The money that we collect through entry fees will be spent on prizes
Directions: It may be necessary to create signs to direct competitors to the event.
Refreshments: (Optional)
Email correspondence: We will have to communicate with clubs to help with promotion and planning.
Project Success Criteria: Our goal is to create and hold a successful video game tournament. We want a turnout of at least 16 people and we want to have all games finished within the time period. To meet this goal, we must get in contact with prospective players through social media, posters, and signs. We also want to get feedback from clubs that have held similar events in the past.

Scope Statement and Work Breakdown Structure for:
Zot Zone Fighting Game Tournament

Tentative Event Date: March 9, 2012
Document Date: February 6, 2012
Prepared by: Team Holy Moly - Raul Plascencia, Kristen Wakamoto, Daniel Lobato, Jeremy Anoc

Scope Statement

Project Summary and Justification:

The team members conceived this project to assist Team Holy Moly in meeting its strategic goals. Promoting and conducting a Street Fighter 4 fighting game tournament at UCI’s Zot Zone will allow Team Holy Moly to gain experience and apply lessons learned from Project Management to a real-world situation. This project is within Team Holy Moly’s capability. We already have a venue for holding the tournament and the cost for reserving this venue will be easily met. The budget for the project is $41, and no additional expenses will be necessary after the project’s completion. It is important for the project to cover, at minimum, the $41 of expenses.

Product Characteristics and Requirements: 

Venue: The venue chosen for this project event is the Zot Zone. The Zot Zone is located in the student center on the second floor, which serves as the main floor and is accessed through ring road. This venue was chosen due to its main purpose of hosting gaming tournaments previously and having the resources to make this project event possible at an affordable price point.
Xbox rentals: The tournament requires the use of multiple Xboxes, since that is the platform that the games must run on. There will be at least 3 Xbox consoles hosting matches simultaneously to ensure that the tournament is progressing as quickly as possible. The Xbox rentals are priced at $1 per hour, in addition to a $1 non-refundable reservation fee for each Xbox. They will be rented for the entire duration of the event.
Promotion: Fliers, a Facebook event page, and word-of-mouth must be utilized to bring attention and attract potential players to the tournament.
Prizes: Prizes will be offered in order to provide some incentive to gamers who are participating in this event. The prizes are in the form of monetary rewards for placing first, second and third. In the event that not many players join the tournament, the prize will only go to the first place winner. The cash for the monetary reward will be provided through the entrance fees of all contestants.
Communication with competitors: In the case of having to make announcements about the tournament project to participants we will be asking for emails addresses from everyone. Furthermore, the Facebook event page will also be utilized for this same purpose being perhaps the easiest method of communicating with others in a manner which most will see fairly quickly.

Summary of Project Deliverables:

Project Management-related Deliverables:

Communication Covenant/Team Contract
Business Case
Scope Statement
Work Breakdown Structure
Gantt chart
Final project presentation
Lessons learned

Product-related Deliverables:

Email correspondence: We will have to communicate with clubs to help with promotion and planning.
Fliers: Paper fliers will be created and posted around campus in order to bring attention to the event.
Promotion: We will create a Facebook event page to provide potential contestants with an easy way to confirm interest in the tournament. The event page will allow us to easily notify contestants of any possible changes to the event. It also will provide us with a head-count to estimate the minimum number of contestants we will have to accommodate.
Bracket: The bracket will list the match-ups between contestants for each round of the competition. It must be kept up-to-date as the tournament progresses.
Prize money: The prize money will come from the contestants’ entry fees.
Directions: It may be necessary to create signs to direct contestants to the event.
Refreshments: If we are able to find a sponsor, we will provide food and/or drinks as an extra incentive to draw in contestants. 

Project Success Criteria: Our goal is to create and hold a successful video game tournament. We want a turnout of at least 16 people and we want to have all games finished within the time period. To meet this goal, we must get in contact with prospective players through social media, fliers, and word-of-mouth. We also want to get feedback from clubs that have held similar events in the past.
